In this phase III trial, 195 patients with lower-risk, non-del(5q) myelodysplastic syndromes were randomized to receive either lenalidomide alone or in combination with erythropoietin alfa. Additionally, the median duration of response was longer in the combination group (23.8 months) than in the monotherapy group (13 months). Another relevant study, registered under NCT00843882, evaluated lenalidomide with or without erythropoietin beta in transfusion-dependent, erythropoiesis-stimulating agent-refractory, lower-risk myelodysplastic syndromes without 5q deletion. This phase III study included 131 patients and reported an erythroid response rate of 39.4% in the combination therapy group versus 23.1% in the lenalidomide monotherapy group. However, the difference in red blood cell transfusion independence between the two groups was not statistically significant. ([pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26500139/?utm_source=openai))

These studies suggest that combining lenalidomide with erythropoietin may enhance erythroid response rates in certain patients with myelodysplastic syndromes.
